SIMPLE: football
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: football
<hw>foot"ball`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An inflated ball to
be kicked in sport, usually made in India rubber, or a bladder incased
in Leather.</def> <rj><au>Waller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>The American <ex>football</ex> is an oblate spheroid, with
pointed ends. In other countries, the <ex>football</ex> is the same as a
soccer ball. The games played with the two different balls are
different. In the United States, the game played with a soccer ball is
called soccer.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The game played with a football{1}, by two opposing
teams of players moving the ball between goals at opposite ends of a
rectangular playing field. Outside the United States <ex>football</ex>
refers to soccer, and in England, also to rugby, but in the United
States the shape of the ball and the rules of the game are
different.</def> <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Soccer or rugby.</def> <mark>[Brit.]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <mark>[fig.]</mark> <def>Something which is treated in a
rough manner, usually as part of a dispute; <as>as, a political
<ex>football</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>footballer</ent>⟦br⟧
